        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 63-year-old woman from the Czech Republic who comes in worried after noticing a breast lump and intermittent nipple discharge, along with mild local irritation and a sense of swelling in the affected breast [SNOMED:C50.9]. She says the changes have made her increasingly anxious over the past several weeks, and she has started checking the area repeatedly in the mirror and avoiding fitted clothing because it makes her more aware of the lump [SNOMED:C50.9].\n\nShe appears well groomed and tired but not acutely ill. {patientName} is retired from office administration and now spends much of her week helping with her grandchildren, gardening on her balcony, and meeting a close friend for coffee. She lives with her husband and describes a supportive family, though she admits she has been keeping some of her fears to herself while waiting for test results. Her appetite is fair and she remains independent in daily activities.\n\nAt home, {patientName} usually keeps an active routine with regular walks and household tasks. Since finding the lump, she has become more distracted and has had trouble sleeping, mostly because she is frightened that the breast changes may represent cancer. She denies dramatic systemic decline and presents mainly because of the breast findings of lump, discharge, irritation, and swelling [SNOMED:C50.9]."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:5c3e9a76-eb77-4797-a004-224a0664a213",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
